<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-284-748  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 284 748.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 26 1990 v24 n13 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Legal eagles train eyes on $48M verdict.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Von Simson, Charles; Nash, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The relationship between computer systems vendors and theircustomers may change in April 1990 when the verdict in a liabilitycase is decided in a US District Court.andP;  Final damages will beawarded in the case of plaintiff Geophysical Systems Corp (GSC), agas and oil exploration firm in Pasadena, CA, versus a softwareand service subsidiary of Raytheon Co, Seismograph Service Co(SSC).andP;  The size of the award will determine the influence of thetrial.andP;  If the full $48 million is awarded, it will be consideredthe largest computer liability to date.andP;  GSC was awarded $48.3million in the first trial in Dec 1988, when seismic dataprocessing software from SSC failed to work as promised.andP;  Anothertrial was set when the judge set aside the damage award becausethe jury did not fully understand the implications of the decisionto throw out the plaintiff's fraud claim.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Geophysical Systems Corp. (cases)Seismograph Service Corp. (cases).andO;Topic:     Computer industryOil IndustrySoftware PublishersLiabilityProduct Failures.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>